## Hey, I just made a Pull Request!

This is a pretty big refactor of the auth backend which moves a lot of existing exports to the `auth-node` package, as well as introduces many new APIs to help build auth provider integrations and modules. The idea is to gradually migrate existing providers to be implemented using these new APIs, while still providing support for the existing auth providers through adapters. Currently only the Google and GCP IAP providers have been migrated.

The primary reason for this refactor is to move out the sign-in logic away from the auth integration itself. That in turn allows for more generic sign-in resolver utilities, and also makes it easier to re-implement a custom auth provider module. For example, a Google provider module with a custom sign-in resolver can be implemented like this:

```ts
export const authModuleGoogleProvider = createBackendModule({
  pluginId: 'auth',
  moduleId: 'googleProvider',
  register(reg) {
    reg.registerInit({
      deps: { providers: authProvidersExtensionPoint },
      async init({ providers }) {
        providers.registerProvider({
          providerId: 'google',
          factory: createOAuthProviderFactory({
            authenticator: googleAuthenticator,
            async signInResolver(info, ctx) {
              // custom resolver ...
            }
          }),
        });
      },
    });
  },
});
```

Along with this new pattern this PR also introduces sign-in resolver factories. They're like the existing functions to create sign-in resolvers, but with the ability to define options that can be passed both through config and code. Configuring sign-in resolvers through config looks like this:

```yaml
auth:
  providers:
    google:
      development:
        clientId: ...
        clientSecret: ...
        signIn:
          resolvers:
            - resolver: emailMatchingUserEntityAnnotation
            - resolver: emailLocalPartMatchingUserEntityName
              enableSomeAdditionalOption: true
```

While this PR doesn't introduce any new sign-in resolvers, the idea is that we'll add more capable ones in the future that help cover most use-cases through configuration alone. The custom module pattern shown above then becomes something that you only need to do very rarely for deeper customizations.

I plan to add some docs for this new API, but probably as a separate guide that we don't promote too much yet. Once we start promoting use of the new backend system we'll switch over the auth docs to this new API instead.

